segments.text: I don't know what's really going on.
I was listening one day when everybody's not black.
I didn't know when they last.
When they last.
I was resting down in Alabama, Mississippi.
I was here during King's Marches.
And the last time I heard about it, I called her dad.
He said, why in the hell aren't you going to deal with it?
Well, see what happened right before that.
Why in the hell?
He said, why in the hell aren't you going to deal with it?
This is a very nice town.
It's not what it ought to be.
But the potential is there.
And we do have some fat-thinking folk in this town.
Well, I guess in all times.
I don't know who to talk to.
Again, I'm going to talk to a lot of them.
Let me ask you, you know, it's not like this area right here.
It's all...
That's the right word.
And I think that's the answer to your problems.
It was just like a fella called me one day and he read to me what I had written.
Daniel and Son Funeral Home.
Suddenly black folk.
I stopped and said, no.
No, he said designed to or something.
I said, no, it was designed to serve anybody.
It just worked out, you see.
I mean, this is honest.
I can bear it down.
I could get another candidate just as good as Severson.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Thank you.
A lot here.
Three lots here cost me $55.
Holy cow, if I got on 29th Street on one lot, it's going to cost me that.
So now again, it's economic.
It's keeping me from my family.
Oh, if you want to go out there and buy, yes.
That's what I'm talking about.
I'm talking about that fuel.
I got a teacher friend out there now.
That's beside the point.
I started to rebuild.
I started to go out to East Park.
But that's not East Park.
It's all Negro.
And if I want to go out there, there's going to be somebody that I'm not going to... That's why I say you're precious.
There's going to be somebody, you know, that's going to be somebody that's going to be a star I'm going to be next to, maybe the same thing I went through tonight.
I could be by my home next to one of you folk that's going to be just as special and not with the damn heat.
See what I'm saying?
So that's why I say, why don't you pay all those treasures every time?
So I'm just as now, we sell... Have you noticed?
I'll tell you what, let me give you another example.
Went to a political meeting the other night.
That was two, four, six slacks.
The first two that went there was I went and another fella.
We sat down.
Here comes the two more.
They came right where we were.
Here come the...
They came right by that four.
See, I'm not mad at them.
Then if you go somewhere, you're not bad by this.
And there are four or five sitting right here.
And I come and sit with y'all.
That's all I'm going to say.
That's all I'm going to say.
That's why.
Everybody wants to be clean, isn't it?
Yeah.
I listened the other day.
Everybody said, uh, I had to have everybody in my mind.
I thought about that.
But, uh, seriously, when I'm sitting here, I like that.
I don't talk about it.
I don't think that's what he should have done.
Because I'm going to have to break it down.
And if you wouldn't, I don't like nothing.
Unless you know me.
Now, if you know me, you might come over and stay a few minutes.
But you don't have to be that long.
But if you're afraid, somebody might say, so-and-so, so-and-so, that is better, and so-and-so, and so-and-so.
They might not put it that way, because nine times, I said it some other way, man.
They might not say it that way to you, because seven times out of ten, you folks are going to have some money.
Three times out of ten, that'd be one of us that'd brag a little.
Am I right, little son?
One of your folk told me I passed out one day.
I was going on Main Street that night.
Not that I wanted to drive a Cadillac, but I got a man.
I've always used him to do this.
One of your folk asked, who's that?
That's that so-and-so.
The man thought he was stupid.
The man told me.
And I know who he is, and I said, I think this is nice.
I'd like to pick him up sometime on the path to me.
I do.
What I'm trying to say is sometimes we're forced to this thing or we're upset.
But you're not going to think about it.
Do you speak out against that?
No.
Not the potent child abuse.
But I was even too young to really know the effects of it, feel the effects of it.
I was too stupid, one of the two.
But I happened to be, and I don't mean to say this braggadociously either, I was fortunate.
Those men always had a few dollars.
Always.
I said, I don't say that braggadociously.
I'm just thankful that he did.
Consequently, whatever happened during that time, as far as I can, it just escaped me.
Just like how she born in 54.
She really stick out the mess.
It was that.
She even escaped the depression.
Because don't think that the depression is hard on you folks.
It was hard on us.
No, it was hard on you all.
Because we've been depressed.
I'm not lying, so to speak.
You folks can't even look at my back depression and say, we've been out of it.
I'm so stiff.
Let me get out of here.
You're supposed to walk around and take a light potty.
Then you'll get, cause I can't do it.
Hey babe, remember we had it nowhere.
I don't have one now.
What about the weather?
Let's talk about the weather.
The weather?
Yeah, has it always been such a new weather around here?
Yes, it is all along.
I remember the weather's been the same.
Maybe yet it's time to get in the hut.
Can you remember how many tornadoes or something at one time?
Yes, I can remember one.
And that happened a pretty long ago.
I came off a film.
I remember the other place where I was.
My dad talked to me.
He had a garage across the street.
And I came in, driving, had something in the back.
And I saw that light on the back when the door was open.
I just thought, you know, lighten up.
And look how hot it was going.
Sure enough.
And the last one.
Because I knew while it was going, the wind was high and it rained like the dust.
That's the only tornado.
And I thought about this no longer than last night.
What happened?
Was it last night?
Yes, last night.
I thought about it at the same time.
Because it was looking just about like it was yesterday.
What about, somebody mentioned that, what is it, what was it, Navistad?
It was 25 miles wide or something.
It had a flag.
Was that years ago?
That was 1900.
Did you hear anything about that?
I only heard about the braggers.
Packers left his bank right here down Bridge Road the last few years.
I went down to see it, and looking at the water, somebody said, that's true, look at it, you didn't see it.
I didn't see it, I didn't see it, there wasn't that much water one time in life, especially around here.

But our water's on, oh, it's about the same, very subtle, we haven't had any terrible, well, let me recall, when I'm from the communes, we don't have something like this, like a few trees, you know what I mean?
Nothing no more than that that I can remember.
What about, I asked you this earlier about the clothing you were wearing.
Like when you were younger, I'm sure, what did the women wear?
Laundry top?
I don't remember again.
I remember one thing, and that was back in 38.
The men, I'm a young man now, they were wearing what is known as drapes.
Daddy had what some people call them pigs.
They're big up here and they're comfortable.
You couldn't get none of the shoes on to save your neck.
But my daddy never would buy me one.
Never would.
Back to kids at school, me, poor me.
I dressed so bad.
What do you mean by bad, Neil?
You just didn't dress in the style?
I didn't.
My dad wouldn't buy it.
And out of all the kids that were there, my dad had money to buy it.
That's just that.
But he always told me, you got plenty of time.
Of course, I appreciate it today, but I didn't end with a damn.
He said, you got plenty of time.
You got plenty of time.
I went to the movies like most of these kids did.
I could almost run fast before I'd go to the movies.
I used to sit in school, and I'd hear these fellas talk about a song hit radio.
Boom, he said, that's so-and-so being played by so-and-so.
I didn't know all that.
But when I went to study in Westwood, I was getting my line from home.
I'd been in certain of getting that little $106,000 slam.
I was dressing like a fool.
I was studying, though.
Don't get me wrong.
I got my show for that.
I don't care for the record store.
I could tell you who it was and what it was playing.
I guess it was in me.
So I don't remember the young men dressing at that time.
I don't know what the ladies were doing, but I do know.
what we were, what they were men.
I wanted to serve them.
Did you live in a, where did you live in New Orleans?
409 West 19, that's right from here on the corner, still there.
My brother and his wife live in there now.
409 West 19.
Do you remember anything about your neighbors, anything that was...
They have all passed on, all those neighbors that were there during my time,
I don't think it's the one living.
I was a kid, that's where it began.
Did your parents have a garden in the back?
No.
Did you buy all your food in the grocery store?
Yeah, did they have, you know, like, big supermarkets like they do now?
No, no, no, no.
They didn't have all that.
Most of you have food coming around.
I'm saddened.
I wish they'd do that today.
Put it around the door and call them drummers.
and stuff like that.
You take my daddy, being a minister and a mortician, he didn't really have time for me.
My mother, like I said, she was a school teacher, and then she actually put me in school, she started teaching music.
Then for years she played music for that church there.
So she wouldn't have had the time to with me.
He or she wouldn't have had time for me at all.
Do you think people that you said were drummers?
Well, we called them a drummer.
They'd come out, come out and be selling clothing, come out selling vests and so forth.
We called them the day truck packers.
On the wagon.
What about the churches?
You were talking about churches.
Have you seen any changing, you know, changes in religion?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
In who?
In what?
In religion?
No, religion doesn't change.
Well, I mean, excuse me.
But the folk, yeah, the folk used to go to church.
They don't go to church no more.
Not religion.
Now, we all have a religion now.
I'm talking about the one that we should be talking about.
That one, that religion doesn't change.
Now, we change.
I've seen the time.
We were talking about that yesterday.
That church right there, we had a man by the name of U.S. Keeling.
He passed a year ago.
Well, it wasn't that church, the old church.
If you want to get in that church, and it was a big one, bought from the first time the church...
In fact, during this political meeting at 12 o'clock at the Capitol table last Friday, I was talking to two or a couple of our friends.
I was about to check on them.
If you want to get a seat tonight, you've got to go two feet out of here tonight.
That's a fact.
That's a fact.
You couldn't get nine-nine at all.
Tonight, how can you do good and get thirty-four this night?
Now, what it is, I don't know.
But religion itself, it ain't going to get hard.
I think we've got more to do.
Well, not that we couldn't do it some other time.
We've got a boat in the yard now, and we'd be ready to go on a trip, and we'd be going to Rance's Pass.
Now, I did it once.
That's something I didn't do.
We were going to Rance's Pass.
In fact, we wanted to come go with him Saturday morning for a date.
Now, he's coming today anyway.
We left that Sunday morning area, and every time I pass a church going, I think I just, I don't know, just get me, because that's something I don't do.
And I went on down there.
I didn't catch a darn thing.
In fact, I left carrying two boats, my boat and that.
And I just went along to fish that Monday.
I didn't get a bite.
And the weather was bad.
I don't know.
I can say it's not so much the religion.
The religion has changed.
We have changed.
See, at that time when everybody was going, we couldn't afford a boat.
We couldn't afford nothing to pull it with, much less the boat.
But now we've got two cars of chicken here parked.
And I think that's what has changed.
The good Lord has blessed us too much.
Well, religion, did it used to play a big part in the family life?
Yes.
A lot more than it does today.
Yeah, again, again, back to what I'm saying.
We didn't have nothing but that.
But now we can do what we want to do.
We got a few dollars and go where we want to go, you know.
Then, too, at that time, that's where all the girls were, too, you know.
Oh, yes, girls, it's just, it's just not more so now, you know.
Well, the activities haven't changed.
They're the same.
I went then because maybe I had to go, but it did something for me now that I go now and I don't have to go.
I go now because I love to go.
Yet I have this as much fun as those folks that don't go.
I have fun when I'm there, and I have fun when I leave there.
I say, I can get the robot out to the Lord, and I get as much fun Monday as I get Sunday, couldn't I?
Well, you might say, well, that man has to work on Sunday, or on a Monday.
Yes, then go Saturday.
I think somewhere it says six days of that late, and do all that work.
So it's like, it's changed what we're living with.
This is skipping around now, but can you remember your grandparents?
Oh, yes.
Can you tell me anything that was outstanding about them that you can remember particularly well?
I don't know how it would be outstanding, but I do know my grandfather was a terrible fellow.
He was out the same house three times.
I forget how many acres out there.
And most of the folk, black folk, had moved to town, so my father...
Talked him into setting out into LeBron, too, because had I known then as I know now, that acreage would have still been there, and I'd have had it.
Because since that time, I acquired somebody in bed.
I didn't, of course, the tent was only four miles out there.
So he had him to move right here on Logan and 20th.
They passed seven years back when my grandmother passed.
I was living in New Pass.
I was in Philadelphia.
I didn't get to come to this room at all.
But they sold out and came to Brown.
She was a lovely person.
He always talked about her.
I don't know what that man called her.
He said, you have more house.
And he had a sister.
You know, sometime, I think you all called the Black Sheep in the family.
When he went to school, some folk told me my grandmother gave him the check.
Now, he don't do that.
My daddy said every time he'd run down, that's when he'd know about my poor hollow on the bicycle, I'd buy it.
My stepson, I really want your dad, I'm not kidding.
He'd tell me, he'd say, every time I run to buy a bicycle, my dad would buy me a brand new horse and bike.
He wouldn't buy me nothing.
But instead, when he went to my house, she'd give him a check, and she'd be talking about how he didn't run through with it.
My daddy was different most of the time.
And I think I kind of a little rubbed off on me.
I'm not as different, but I got a lot of them.
And my two brothers, they're doctors.
I have two twin brothers down here.
They're doctors.
We get them checked with what we want to.
They even sell the checkbook.
Talking about checkbooks, do they always have banks?
Can you remember?
Well, as long as I can remember, they had banks.
Was there any prejudice in the banking system at that time?
Well, let's put it this way.
There's still prejudice in the banking system at that time.
Of course, they're getting better.
And they're getting better now because several of them, one in particular, has got no organ.
Then, too, the next growers have a little bit more money to ask for.
They're going to have to kind of put their hand out and kind of talk about getting that dollar first.
Oh, the dollar looks the same to get it paid.
It is better if it pays to get it.
It does get paid.
You talking about borrowing money?
It wouldn't be a better idea than that.
back in 1955.
I was going to be able to turn home down there.
A brown-bearded, long-headed man by the name of Ernest Langford.
He was a Hellcat till the day he died.
He is in Hell now, looking up, hoping somebody comes to him with his tongue.
And anybody that's present means, yeah, they can't get away with it.
Because if they hit him, I don't want to go.
If he's hit him, I don't want to go.
That's a fact.
He met my wife one day.
But anyway, I wanted to borrow money.
Well, after I came out of service, I wanted to be in their house.
And on paper, the house wasn't close enough.
But I had a house down at, he told me at the time, that was in
Boy, I was living in 507 West 19th Street with my father.
I'd married then.
Boy,
You go find something called $3,000 I'll talk with you.
I said, hell.
I said, what do you mean something like $3,000?
I said, that's where I am.
That's where I live.
And I said, man, I'm kind of mean.
That's more than the one that I was talking about.
And I said, I grabbed my mean stick from him because my daddy was the most easy to try to get us off.
Unless you made him hard.
Back in the day, the man would break through the cars, and he always said, like, you better not do that.
That's all he said.
Because he had one of that boys.
You better not do that.
With me?
Well, his map is the best, of course.
His map is the best.
I went to a business meeting with him one night, and I thought for a reason.
Yeah, I only heard about two of them.
They're getting a good map back in Lincoln, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
That's right.
One of the old deacons got up.
The pastor wanted us to send him to the National Baptist Convention.
He said, brother, older, he said the National Baptist Convention meeting in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, I'm going.
That's what he said to me tonight.
But see, I'd have at least wrapped my ear in something.
You know what, though, really?
It would be nice if more folk like you would get the message across.
It would be better than any edict that the Congress will ever pass.
Because don't fool yourself.
That's some good black folk.
Then there are some that are worth a damn.
And that's some good white folk.
I'm going to give you an example of that.
over me.
No, I said, I'm against so-and-so, so I'll be out of credit.
And I said, why?
And they said, excuse me.
I don't know, man.
I just got mad.
What the?
Oh, this preacher.
I talk about that every day.
I can't go for that kind of stuff.
Because sometimes, or some people, and some people too, I don't want to open it.
But not only because he's an equal, not because he's not.
And that's what I said.
The preacher can take
I went out there.
That's the scone of the other guy, I tell you now.
Had she not been there, I wouldn't have gone.
But then after I started letting them come, I became involved.
Now I tell you another thing, I'm fighting.
Since we got Brian High here, I'm waiting to see now when they're going to finally find a Negro that's going to come speak to Baccalaureate Summit.
You see, now I'm sure some of you folks can tell us something, and some of my folks can tell y'all something.
I just mentioned a good one, Barbara Judge.
Out of all the professors you got at A&M, I think she'll stand toe-to-toe with whoever.
Thanks for two people together.
Because when you find one of us that has excelled or does excel, don't fool yourself.
You've got to excel sometimes.
And she's one of them.
You hear me?
See, I like to tell the whole group of black people about this same thing.
And that's what's going to get the same spread.
For black people.
Because you're going to be more involved than...
the lady here, because she hasn't really been identified with it.
You've been involved in it.

But you haven't been involved to the extent where if you and another white fellow is coming up the road there, and one of us is going to walk and kick me, and then you see me whooping, you're going to turn in and help him.
You're going to turn in and help him.
I'll whoop both of y'all in before you try to polish.
It's kind of like I had two friends fight one day.
Hang on.
I had two friends fight one day, and I'm a friend of this one, I'm a friend of this one.
One of them said, which one are you going to punch?
And I thought about it.
It wasn't.
Just punch.
So instead of you punching, you're going to have to take side.
That tells me how far you've come out of where you were.
Would you take side, or would you just punch?
Punch.
Let's talk about food.
We haven't talked about food.
Is the food still the same?
No, it's not the same.
I am so hungry.
No, it's not the same.
It's not the same.
I think we've doctored it too much.
We don't get the same value from it we used to.
Not only have we doctored it, we're cooking it different.
Well, what was different?
What can you remember when you were a little kid that you ate?
Well, I eat the same thing now, but like I say, it's been...
Fertilizer death and growing too fast.
We just don't get from it what we used to get.
Then we've gotten these type of cooking utensils.
We've gotten to put all the good stuff out in the drain, you know.
What we throw in our drain, we should be eating.
And that's what we keep.
We should be throwing in our drain.
Well, what is this?
Well, I see that salt food.
What is that?
Who's that?
Salt food.
Salt food.
Salt.
Oh, that's just a common vernacular.
They give the stuff like greens and, well, I must be able to call it greens, chitlins and that kind of mess.
They call it soul.
There's nothing soul about it.
Yeah.
That's just a name they gave to food like that, soul food.
To me, it's nothing.
To me, it's like that dunce thing right on, and I'm just sick of it.
That's just common vernacular.
That's all.
Nothing's soul food.
If I like steak, to me, that's soul food.
If you like baked beans and mustard beans, that's all right.
That's soul food, too.
Is that what you want to call it?
Were there any, like, good restaurants that you've gone to?
Outstanding places?
Outstanding?
No.
We still don't have any.
Wow.
Well... Now, I think the closest thing to, I understand, I went out to...
The tower, the food was very good.
Now, I might say that's outstanding, but I'm putting that in the class of Seth.
It's going to take another, once we get Piccadilly in here to weigh it wider, then we're going to have a good restaurant.
Tell us about some of the food you had when you were back.
I ate the same thing then.
I ate the same thing then.
I'm eating now.
Ten right there.
I'll tell you one thing, every Sunday, my dad would call them short seven steaks, every Sunday.
And I went out to cut for my grandmother, she said, you're going to have a chicken every Sunday.
But the food's about the same.
We can't eat as much as we used to because it's so high.
I told my wife yesterday, she had, for dinner now, I had a strip salad.
I think I had supper last night.
Strip salon.
That's fine.
I said, you can't do strip salon.
Really.
We had strip salon Saturday.
I went for dinner yesterday.
She had to go to school because she came home with her.
I had strip salon again last night.
So food hasn't changed since the price has gone up.
And one thing about food, like she said, she said, I'm working.
I'm eating a little.
Let's get through.
And I can't much blame her, but I don't see that.
We've done that, though.
Oh, I'm sorry.
Well, what about, do you remember that building of Highway 6?
No, I can't remember the building of Highway 6 now.
I don't remember when it was.
I don't know whether I remember that or what.
I can't recall.
What about, have you heard of Peach Creek?
Yes, I've heard of Peach Creek.
I don't know where that is, but I've heard of Peach Creek.
I don't know what it is.
We just talked about it in class, you know, somebody mentioned Peach Creek.
Well, I've heard of Peach Creek all right.
I just don't know what to mention.
I don't know.
I've heard of Peach Creek.
What about the railroad?
Can you think of anything?
Yeah.
I asked you that before, but...
The railroad, uh...
I can't think what year it was, man.
What did you call that thing?
The Zephyr.
That song was just a smooth ride in the car.
And the first day to come through here, everybody came through at 10-something and 12-something, I believe.
10-something going to Dallas, 12-something going to Houston.
And the first day it was to come through was like a raid up there, man.
That big, you came through, just flashed all his brakes, set out like a car.
It was a pretty thing.
Fast.
Was everybody standing there watching?
Oh, yes.
They were there.
They talked about Amtrak, but Amtrak can't be might of good if you're equal as that.
Let's talk at A&M.
Let's talk at Brown, A&M, and A&M.
And I don't think it stopped between.
I don't think it did.
I don't understand.
I don't understand.
You folk out there got a wonderful opportunity.
Let me ask you a question.
We had a very large house, but it was heated with wood.
We had out back what we called a wood house.
That was my job at school, make sure that wood was in.
We heated with wood, cooked with wood.
The restroom was outdoors at that time.
I can't remember when we got electricity, but I know eventually when I can remember, we had it.
We bought television the day they came out, that they got the bribe.
We both tell them.
I'm going to tell you a story about that.
Oh, Kraft, he won't tell anyone tonight because I've been mad.
And Kraft had closed.
So I called up, Daddy, we closed.
What do you want?
I said, I want to tell you.
He said, oh, hell, they went and closed.
